            <term xml:id="term-k000163-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">dilou</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">敵樓</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">敌楼</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">dílóu</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">ti-lo</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000163-3">resisting tower</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-7" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000163-1">turret</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000163-8" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000163-2">defense tower</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000163</idno>
            <!-- <note type="Gloss"> 
               <p xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000163-1">turret (Levine 2014, 75; Huang 2001, 49); defense tower (Feng 2012, 94); usually added to the tops of a <term ref="/keyword/k000121">mamian ("horse face")</term>, <term ref="/keyword/k000089">wengcheng ("Urn-shaped city wall")</term>, or a jiaolou ("corner tower"); literally: "resisting" tower  (Kroll 2015, 82)</p>   
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant" source="#biblk000163-2">中國古代的軍事防禦設施 (Feng 2012, 94)。多設于<term ref="/keyword/k000121">馬面</term>之上、<term ref="/keyword/k000089">甕城</term>之上以及城角之上。</p>               
            </note> -->
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lang="en">The term di 敵 means to “resist or fight against the enemy” (HYDCD 2.0 Digital 2002), and lou 樓 refers to “a one-story or multi-story military fortification built on city 
                  walls or high platforms” or “a tall building with multiple stories” (CMW S21 et al., 2023). Together, dilou 敵樓 are facilities used to defend against a millitary opponent. </p>
               <p xml:lang="en">The term dilou first appeared in the <term ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang</term> dynasty in reference to military facilities protruding outward from a city wall, usually placed at intervals (Fang 618–907, 5a). 
                  In the <term ref="/keyword/k000074">Song</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000101">Yuan</term> dynasties, the description of dilou became more specific, and most of the dilou on the city walls were wooden structures that are flush with the city wall or 
                  protruded slightly outward from the wall  (Zeng 1599, 12.2a) (Fig. 1). Dilou were also built on warships (Zeng 960–1279, 7.4a).</p>
               <p xml:lang="en">During the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasties, especially in the mid-to-late Ming, the term dilou was used more frequently in textual sources, and the forms of the actual buildings 
                  became more varied. Depending on their form, they can be divided into two types: the first type is built on high ground, mostly of one to three stories（Qi 1592, 13.11a）and are 
                  frequently built on the city wall (Zeng 1599, 12.2a). They can also be detached from the wall, and built on top of other free-standing military structures (Zhang 1613, 44.10b). 
                  The second type is the hollow, multi-storey dilou 敵樓, which were  built on the Great Wall (Tan 1819, 2.43a) or could be independently located in geopolitically sensitive areas 
                  (Huang 1628–1644, 2.10b). In this function, it is  similar in form and function to the hollow kongxin duntai 空心墩臺 (also called ditai 敵臺).</p>   
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">從字義上看，“敵”指“抵擋、對抗敵人”(漢語大詞典2.0電子版2002)，“樓”指“築於城牆或高臺上一層或多層的軍事防備建築”或“本身高聳的多層建築”（CMW S21 et al，2023）。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">“敵樓”一詞最早出現於唐代，指城墻上向外突出的軍事設施，一般間隔一段距離設置一座（方618－907，5a）。宋元時期，“敵樓”的描述更加具體，城墻上的敵樓多為木構，沿城墻直起或略向外挑出（曾1599，12.2a）
                  （圖1）。此外，還出現了建造在戰船上的敵樓（章960－1279，7.4a）。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">明清時期，特別是明中後期，文献中“敵樓”一詞的使用頻次增多，敵樓的形態更加丰富。根據形態，明清時期的敵樓可分為兩類：一是建造在高處的敵樓，多為一到三層（戚1592，13.11a），常見於城墻上
                  （曾1599，12.2a），或其他獨立的軍事設施上（章1613，44.10b）。二是自身高聳，內部空心多層的敵樓，可築於長城上（譚1819，2.43a），或獨立設置於戰略要地（黃1628—1644，2.10b），這類敵樓的形製和功能與空心墩台、敵台十分
                  類似。</p>   
            </note>
